#14. Run the ‘tail -f /var/log/syslog‘ command in background

tail -f /var/log/syslog &

# may need sudo if permission is denied.
#man sudo - execute a command as another user
##man su - substitute user identity
#man tail (diplay the last part of a file)  normally the last 10 lines of file unless otherwise specified
#-f == causes 'tail' to not stop when end of file is reached, but rather to wait for additional data to be appended to the input
# & == control operator, telling the shell to execute the command in the background in a subshell.
